#!/usr/bin/env bash
# In-workspace cheatsheet for the on-cluster Android device.
#   mobile-help            full command list (also: device help)
#   mobile-help --banner   the terminal greeting (used on shell start)
if [ "${1:-}" = "--banner" ]; then
  printf '\033[1m\360\237\223\261 Mobile Dev\033[0m \342\200\224 \033[1myour device, you run it:\033[0m '
  printf '\033[1mdevice start\033[0m \302\267 \033[1mdevice stop\033[0m \302\267 '
  printf '\033[1mdevice help\033[0m for all commands\n'
  exit 0
fi
cat <<'EOF'

📱 Mobile Dev — YOUR on-cluster Android device. One command: `device`

  ── lifecycle (yours to run) ─────────────────────────────────────────────
  device start      START: create the device — run this FIRST (also wakes a
                    stopped device; safe to re-run any time).
  device stop       STOP when you're done: halts the VM + screen, keeps the
                    disk, frees ~4 CPU / 4Gi RAM. Workspace sleep does NOT
                    stop the device — stopping it is on you.
  device remove     DELETE the device + its disk entirely. (Deleting the
                    whole workspace also removes it automatically.)

  ── daily use ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  device status     Is my device up? Shows boot state + its live-screen URL.
  device watch      Full status refreshed on screen — Ctrl-C to exit.
  device run        Build + install + LAUNCH the app on the device (prints the screen URL).
  device screen     Print the device's live-screen URL (open it in a browser tab).
  device restart    Reboot a frozen device (keeps the disk).

  Web preview (no device needed):  Terminal → Run Task → "Web preview", or run:
    flutter build web --profile --base-href / && python3 -m http.server 8080 --bind 0.0.0.0 --directory build/web

  Notes:
   • First-ever `device start` takes several minutes (imports the VM image);
     later starts/wakes are ~1–2 min.
   • Can't create the device (Forbidden)? Ask your admin for VM provisioning
     rights in your namespace (the platform grants the built-in 'edit' role via
     Dev Spaces — see the platform README).
   • On the screen, pick a decoder: WebCodecs (Chrome/Edge) or Broadway.js (Firefox).
   • Full guide: README.md   •   this help again: device help

EOF
